# Kuhli Loach: The Burrowing Architects of the Aquarium

Kuhli Loaches (*Pangio kuhlii*) are the shy, eel-like scavengers that disappear into substrate and decorations the moment lights come on — only to emerge at night as tireless cleaners of every uneaten food particle on the bottom. Their serpentine body, tiger-banded colouration, and habit of piling together in group resting spots make them one of the most characterful nano and community fish in the hobby. Keeping them well requires understanding their social needs, their softwater origin, and their absolute requirement for a safe, fine substrate to burrow into.

---

## Natural Habitat

In the wild, Kuhli Loaches inhabit the shallow, heavily vegetated, leaf-littered streams of Southeast Asia — the Malaysian peninsula, Sumatra, Java, and Borneo. These are classic blackwater and clearwater biotope streams: soft, acidic, warm, low-flow, with substrate of fine sand, leaf litter, and detritus.

The wild diet consists of micro-invertebrates, small worms, bottom-dwelling insects, and organic debris sifted from substrate. Their elongated body is perfectly adapted for pushing through substrate and root tangles in pursuit of food hidden below the surface.

Understanding this habitat defines their care requirements: soft water, warm temperatures, fine substrate, dense coverage, low current, and dim or diffuse lighting.

---

## Species Identification

Several *Pangio* species are sold under the name "Kuhli Loach":

**Pangio kuhlii** — The true Kuhli. Yellow-orange body with 12–17 dark brown to black bands that don't reach the belly. Bands are irregular and may merge or split.

**Pangio semicincta** (Half-banded Kuhli) — Very similar to *kuhlii*; bands don't extend as far down the sides. Often sold interchangeably.

**Pangio anguillaris** (Slimy Myersi / Coolie Loach) — Darker, more uniform colouration. Sometimes sold as "black Kuhli."

All share essentially identical care requirements. Mixed-species groups are fine in the hobby context.

