## Feeding

Kuhli Loaches are omnivorous micro-predators and scavengers. In the wild they eat small worms, insect larvae, tiny crustaceans, and organic detritus.

### Staple Foods

**Sinking pellets / wafers** — Must reach the bottom before other fish consume them. Feed after lights out for best results (Kuhli Loaches are nocturnal).

**Sinking mini granules** — Small granule size appropriate for their small mouths.

**Frozen bloodworms** — Highly relished. Drop directly to substrate.

**Frozen tubifex worms** — Excellent; mirrors the tubificid worms they consume in nature.

### Live Foods

Live foods are ideal for both nutrition and stimulation of natural foraging behaviour:

**Blackworms (*Lumbriculus variegatus*)** — The single best live food for Kuhli Loaches. Live blackworms burrow into substrate, triggering intense natural foraging behaviour as loaches pursue them through the sand. Excellent nutrition and behavioural enrichment.

**Micro worms** — Excellent for smaller/younger loaches. **[Available at Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**

**Baby Brine Shrimp** — Sinking nauplii reach the substrate zone and are actively hunted. **[Live BBS from Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**

**Daphnia** — Some will be eaten in water column; some settle and are consumed from substrate. **[Available at Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**

**[Explore live food cultivation guides on the Blackwater Aquatics Knowledge Base](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/blogs/knowledge-base).**

### Feeding Timing

Feed after lights out or as part of a "night feeding" schedule (dim the lights, wait 30 minutes, then feed). This ensures loaches get adequate food before surface-feeding fish consume it all.

