## Health and Disease

### Ich (*Ichthyophthirius multifiliis*)

Kuhli Loaches lack scales on most of their body — the small embedded scales on their back provide minimal protection. This makes them more susceptible to ich and more sensitive to ich treatments.

**Heat treatment** (raised to 30°C for 2+ weeks with increased aeration) is the preferred ich treatment — avoids medication toxicity. Kuhli Loaches tolerate 30°C for 2 weeks without harm.

**Medication caution:** Kuhli Loaches are sensitive to many aquarium medications due to scalelessness. Always use half-doses of any medication and monitor closely. Avoid salt-based treatments — they are softwater fish and poorly tolerate salinity.

### Internal Parasites

Newly acquired loaches commonly harbour internal parasites. Signs include: sunken belly despite eating, stringy white faeces, unexplained weight loss. Treat with Levamisole or Praziquantel. Quarantine all new fish.

### Bacterial Infections

Usually follow stress, injury, or poor water conditions. Fin fraying, white patches, or lesions respond to water quality improvement and targeted antibiotics if severe.

### Skinny Disease

Progressive weight loss in well-fed fish. Usually internal parasites or mycobacteria. Difficult to reverse once advanced.

